"Hemp A.","Climate change-driven forest fires marginalize the impact of ice cap wasting on Kilimanjaro",2005,"Global Change Biology","11","7",,"1013","1023",,,10.1111/j.1365-2486.2005.00968.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-27744526685&partnerID=40&md5=c502fb456e29c28296fb129832cf4a90","Department of Plant Physiology, University of Bayreuth, Universitätsstr. 30, 95445 Bayreuth, Germany","Hemp, A., Department of Plant Physiology, University of Bayreuth, Universitätsstr. 30, 95445 Bayreuth, Germany","The disappearing glaciers of Kilimanjaro are attracting broad interest. Less conspicuous but ecologically far more significant is the associated increase of frequency and intensity of fires on the slopes of Kilimanjaro, which leads to a downward shift of the upper forest line by several hundred meters as a result of a drier (warmer) climate since the last century. In contrast to common belief, global warming does not necessarily cause upward migration of plants and animals. Here, it is shown that on Kilimanjaro the opposite trend is under way, with consequences more harmful than those due to the loss of the showy ice cap of Africa's highest mountain. © 2005 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.","Alpine vegetation; Climate change; East Africa; Erica; Forest fires; Montane; Subalpine cloud forest; Vegetation change; Vegetation zones","climate change; cloud forest; forest fire; mountain environment; treeline; vegetation dynamics; Africa; East Africa; Eastern Hemisphere; Kilimanjaro [Kilimanjaro (RGN)]; Kilimanjaro [Tanzania]; Sub-Saharan Africa; Tanzania; World; Animalia; Erica",,,,,,"Altmann, J., Alberts, S.C., Altmann, S.A., Dramatic change in local climate patterns in the Amboseli basin, Kenya (2002) African Journal of Ecology, 40, pp. 248-251; Braun-Blanquet, J., (1964) Pflanzensoziologie, , Springer, Wien; Bruijnzeel, L.A., (1990) Hydrology of Moist Tropical Forests and Effects of Conversion: A State of Knowledge Review, , Free University, Amsterdam; Bruijnzeel